# Propose a draft response to a GitHub issue

**Inputs**:
- The issue record (from `detect-issues.prompt`), including
  `cycle_count`.
- `cycle_count` (integer ≥ 1) — passed in by the orchestrator and
  used to locate the current cycle's upstream artefacts and to
  shape the draft's tone (see "Cycle-aware tone" below).
- The triage verdict at
  `../output-github-issues/issue-<N>/cycle-<C>/triage.md`.
- For Flow B issues, the impact analysis at
  `../output-github-issues/issue-<N>/cycle-<C>/impact.md` — in
  particular its `## Issue disposition` block, which is the
  source of truth for the binary conclusion the response MUST
  carry (see "Issue conclusion" below).
- When `cycle_count > 1`, the prior cycle's response at
  `../output-github-issues/issue-<N>/cycle-<C-1>/response.md` —
  the draft must acknowledge it (and the OP's reply to it)
  without restating it verbatim.
- The issue's `meta.md` at
  `../output-github-issues/issue-<N>/meta.md` — gives the current
  comments timeline; useful when the response needs to reference
  what the OP said in their last reply.
- The full project tree (`../context/`, `../output/`,
  `../output-analysis/`, `../README.md`, `../CLAUDE.md`,
  `../.project/`) — used to ground the response and to ensure the
  draft does NOT contradict an existing requirement, ADR, or
  active design decision.

**Output**: `../output-github-issues/issue-<N>/cycle-<C>/response.md`.
Plain markdown, ready to paste into `gh issue comment --body-file`.

**Skip if**:
`../output-github-issues/issue-<N>/cycle-<C>/response.md` exists
AND its mtime is newer than the triage file's mtime AND (if Flow
B) newer than the impact file's mtime. If any upstream artefact
moved, the response is stale and must be rewritten. A new cycle
folder is always empty when first created, so this skip naturally
applies only when the same cycle is being re-run.

**Execution mode**: never invoked when `triage.flow == SKIP`. The
anti-loop cap (D5, `cycle_count >= 4`) is enforced upstream by
`detect-issues` — by the time this prompt runs, the cycle index
is guaranteed to be in `{1, 2, 3}`.

---

## Output language

The draft MUST be written in the language stored as `lang` in the
triage verdict (D4 fallback: `en`). All headings, prose, code
comments inside fenced blocks, and the closing line stay in the
detected language. Technical terms (`OverlayPresentation`,
`ListMPD`, `DASH 6th`, `SCTE-35`) are kept verbatim regardless of
the language — they are proper nouns of the spec.

## Mandatory marker

Every response, regardless of flow or severity, MUST end with the
following hidden HTML comment on its own final line:

```html
<!-- sgai-issues: ai-cycle -->
```

This marker is what the triage step (`triage-issue.prompt`) uses
to count AI cycles for the anti-loop cap (D5). The marker is
invisible in GitHub's rendered view but readable when the body is
fetched via the API.

## Severity-driven disclaimer (D3)

If `triage.severity == "requirements"` OR
`triage.severity == "architectural"`, the draft MUST open with
this exact disclaimer line (translated into `triage.lang`):

- **`en`**: *"This response was auto-drafted by the project's AI
  agent — please cross-check with project owner before relying on
  it."*
- **`es`**: *"Esta respuesta fue auto-redactada por el agente AI
  del proyecto — por favor, cruzar referencias con el dueño del
  proyecto antes de basarse en ella."*
- **`pt`**: *"Esta resposta foi rascunhada automaticamente pelo
  agente IA do projeto — por favor, valide com o dono do projeto
  antes de confiar nela."*
- **`fr`**: *"Cette réponse a été rédigée automatiquement par
  l'agent IA du projet — merci de vérifier auprès du responsable
  du projet avant de vous y fier."*
- **`it`**: *"Questa risposta è stata redatta automaticamente
  dall'agente IA del progetto — vi preghiamo di verificare con il
  proprietario del progetto prima di affidarvi a essa."*
- **`de`**: *"Diese Antwort wurde automatisch vom KI-Agenten des
  Projekts entworfen — bitte vor der Verwendung mit dem
  Projektverantwortlichen abgleichen."*

Format the disclaimer as a blockquote (`> …`) so it stands out
visually.

For `severity ∈ {cosmetic, spec-detail}` the disclaimer is NOT
added — those responses don't carry decision weight, and front-
loading a disclaimer on every minor reply would dilute its signal.

## Cycle-aware tone

`cycle_count == 1` is the default case: the AI is responding to
the issue for the first time. No special framing.

When `cycle_count > 1`, the OP has replied to a previous AI
response and the pipeline is preparing a follow-up. The draft
MUST:

1. Open with a brief acknowledgement of the prior cycle. Example
   phrasings (in the detected language; English here):
   - "Thanks for the follow-up — to the new points raised:"
   - "Following up on the previous reply: addressing the new
     feedback below."
   The acknowledgement is one sentence at most; do NOT recap what
   was said before — the OP and the maintainer can scroll up.
2. Focus the body on the **new** material from the OP. Do NOT
   re-litigate claims that were already validated in
   `cycle-<C-1>/impact.md`; treat them as settled unless the OP
   explicitly contests them in their reply.
3. Keep the severity-driven disclaimer (D3) and the closing marker
   `<!-- sgai-issues: ai-cycle -->` exactly as on cycle 1. The
   marker is what `detect-issues` counts on the next run.
4. **Issue-conclusion continuity**: when `cycle_count > 1` AND the
   prior cycle's conclusion was `NEEDS-NEXT-STEP`, the draft MUST
   explicitly state whether the OP's new reply flipped the
   conclusion to `RESOLVED-BY-RESPONSE` (and why — which action
   items got cleared by the OP's clarification, or which pointer
   the OP now accepts), OR kept it `NEEDS-NEXT-STEP` (and which
   action items remain unresolved, plus any new ones the OP's
   reply surfaced). This is the load-bearing info for the
   maintainer — without it they cannot tell whether the issue can
   now be closed or still needs follow-up. Mirror the pattern
   Stage 6 applies to its mergeable conclusion across cycles.

## Issue conclusion (D14)

Orthogonal to the four-way flow above, every response MUST end
with a **binary conclusion** about what the maintainer should do
with the issue after reading the reply:

- **`RESOLVED-BY-RESPONSE`** (`conclusion: resolved`) — the AI's
  response already covers what the issue raiser asked for. The
  maintainer may close the issue.
- **`NEEDS-NEXT-STEP`** (`conclusion: needs-next-step`) — the
  issue requires action that the response itself does not provide
  (a future spec change, an ADR, WG input, a clarification from
  the raiser, etc.). The maintainer should keep the issue open
  and act on the listed next steps.

The flow (`A` / `B` / `C`) characterises **what the AI did**; the
conclusion characterises **what the maintainer / WG / raiser does
next**. They are orthogonal — a Flow A "pointer-style" reply is
typically `RESOLVED-BY-RESPONSE`, but a Flow A question that
exposes a documentation gap can be `NEEDS-NEXT-STEP` (the action
item is "open a docs PR"); a Flow B "incorporate" recommendation
is virtually always `NEEDS-NEXT-STEP` (the action item is "open
a context/ PR"); a Flow B "no change required, the spec already
covers it" is `RESOLVED-BY-RESPONSE`.

### Decision rules

Set `conclusion: resolved` (RESOLVED-BY-RESPONSE) when **ALL** of
the following hold:

1. The response itself covers what the issue raiser asked for —
   examples:
   - Missing context the raiser was unaware of (Flow A pointer to
     `README.md` / `CLAUDE.md` / `.project/PROJECT.md`).
   - A clarification of an existing decision already recorded in
     `.project/decisions/` or `context/` (Flow B "no change
     required").
   - A link to an external authoritative document (a published
     standard section, a working-group decision) that answers the
     raiser's question.
2. The issue is a duplicate of something already documented or
   decided. Cite the source (existing ADR, existing issue,
   existing requirement / UC ID).
3. OR the issue is out-of-scope for this project and clarifiably
   archivable (point the raiser at the right venue, e.g. an
   upstream repo or a WG mailing list).
4. **AND** no change is required to the spec or to any downstream
   artefact — no follow-up PR, no ADR, no WG discussion, no
   clarification from the raiser.

Set `conclusion: needs-next-step` (NEEDS-NEXT-STEP) when **ANY**
of:

- The issue requires a future change to the spec — a new
  requirement, a modified UC, a new construct, a renamed
  attribute, a corrected wording — i.e. a PR against `context/`.
- The issue requires a new architectural decision — an ADR in
  `.project/decisions/`.
- The issue requires WG discussion or external input that is not
  available locally (e.g. a contested DASH 6th interpretation
  that needs to be resolved with the WG).
- The issue requires a clarification from the issue raiser
  before the AI can respond on the merits (the raiser's question
  is ambiguous and the AI's response asks them to refine it).
- The AI's response is only a partial answer — the spec
  maintainer, the WG, or the raiser still has work to do.

For Flow B issues, the disposition is **already declared** by
`analyze-impact.prompt` in `impact.md` under
`## Issue disposition`. The draft MUST adopt that disposition
verbatim (mapping `RESOLVED-BY-RESPONSE` ↔ `resolved` and
`NEEDS-NEXT-STEP` ↔ `needs-next-step`). If the impact analysis
and the draft disagree, the analysis wins — fix the draft. If
the disagreement is load-bearing (the draft writer has a strong
reason to believe the analysis got the disposition wrong), log
the discrepancy in the draft body and surface it for human
review rather than overriding silently.

For Flow A and Flow C issues, no `impact.md` exists; the draft
writer decides the conclusion directly from the response
content, against the rules above.

### Section placement and content

Append a new `## Issue conclusion` section to the response draft
**after** the flow-appropriate body and **before** the closing
`<!-- anti-contradiction: ok -->` (Flow A) and the closing
`<!-- sgai-issues: ai-cycle -->` marker. The section MUST start
with the binary verdict on its own line:

```markdown
## Issue conclusion

**RESOLVED-BY-RESPONSE** — <one-line reason>
```

OR

```markdown
## Issue conclusion

**NEEDS-NEXT-STEP** — <one-line reason>
```

Translate the heading and the inline reason into `triage.lang`.
The binary token (`RESOLVED-BY-RESPONSE` / `NEEDS-NEXT-STEP`)
stays in English regardless — it is a status token, not prose.

#### When `RESOLVED-BY-RESPONSE`

Close with a short **closing rationale** paragraph (2–4
sentences) explaining:

- Why the response covers what the raiser asked (cite the
  pointer used: file path, decision ID, requirement ID, external
  source).
- A direct suggestion to the maintainer that the issue may be
  closed.

Tone: direct, not condescending toward the raiser. Phrasing like
"this can be closed" is fine; do NOT lecture the raiser on why
they should have known.

#### When `NEEDS-NEXT-STEP`

Close with a `### Next steps` block listing **concrete action
items**. Use a bulleted list, one action per bullet. Each action
MUST identify:

- **Actor** — who should act: `Nicolas` (project owner),
  `WG` (working group / external standards body), `emilsas`
  (collaborator) or `<github-handle>`, `the issue raiser` (when
  clarification is what's needed), or `maintainer` (catch-all
  when the actor depends on who picks it up first).
- **Artefact type** — what kind of artefact the action produces:
  `PR` (a pull request, typically against `context/`), `ADR` (a
  decision record under `.project/decisions/`), `follow-up issue`
  (a new GitHub issue tracking the work), `clarification` (a
  reply from the raiser asking for more detail), `WG discussion`
  (escalation to a working group venue), `docs update` (a
  non-spec doc tweak — README, CLAUDE.md, .project/PROJECT.md).
- **Brief** — one-line description of what the artefact must
  contain or resolve.

If multiple options exist (e.g. "could be a PR OR an ADR"), the
AI MUST mark its recommendation explicitly:

```markdown
### Next steps

- **Nicolas** — `ADR` — Decide whether `ListMPD` should mandate
  `@id` uniqueness across nested lists. **Recommended**: ADR
  rather than a context/ tweak, because the question is
  architectural (touches the construct's invariants).
- **WG** — `WG discussion` — Bring the construct's invariants
  to the next DASH-IF SAI call for cross-vendor validation.
```

Tone: actionable, not vague. "Discuss this further" is NOT a
next step; "Bring construct X invariants to the next DASH-IF SAI
call" is.

## Flow-specific draft shape

### Flow A — Meta about the project

Goal: explain how the project / repo / pipeline works, in the
author's language, with concrete pointers.

Structure:

1. **Acknowledge** the question in one short sentence.
2. **Answer** the question directly with 1–3 paragraphs. Cite
   specific files using their repo path (e.g. `prompts/README.md`,
   `CLAUDE.md`, `.project/PROJECT.md`). Use markdown links of the
   form `[name](path)` so GitHub renders them.
3. **3 propose-context suggestions** (mandatory for Flow A): list
   3 short ideas of what the project could clarify or document
   better, framed as offers the maintainer can adopt or ignore.
   These are NOT decisions — they exist to give Nicolas raw
   material when he reviews the draft. Use a bulleted list.
4. **Anti-contradiction check** (mandatory): re-read the draft
   against `context/03-requirements.md`, the open ADRs in
   `.project/decisions/`, and the "Open threads" list at the
   bottom of `.project/PROJECT.md`. If anything in the draft
   contradicts an established requirement / ADR / open thread,
   FIX the draft before saving. Log the check as the last line
   of the response file:
   `<!-- anti-contradiction: ok -->` (or `... : conflict-with-<id>`
   when the contradiction was unresolvable and the operator must
   review).

### Flow B — Substantive feedback on `context/`

Goal: answer the author on the merits, grounded in the impact
analysis.

Structure:

1. **Acknowledge** the proposal in one short sentence —
   summarise what the author is asking for.
2. **Engage with the claims**: walk through the validated claims
   from `impact.md`. Confirm what's correct, gently correct what's
   refuted (cite the spec section / requirement). Avoid combative
   tone — the author is contributing.
3. **State the recommended action** (mirroring `impact.md`):
   - For `incorporate`: "We will bring this to the next build /
     WG session. Concretely, this would look like: <sketch from
     impact.md>." Mention that the change requires Nicolas's sign-
     off (the author should NOT assume the change is committed).
   - For `partial-incorporate`: explicitly list which parts are
     in and which are out, with reasons.
   - For `reject`: cite the constraint (ADR, requirement,
     existing decision) and explain why. Offer an alternative
     framing if one exists.
   - For `defer`: say what would unblock the decision (a WG
     session, an external standard's resolution, etc.) and a
     rough timeframe if known.
4. **Close** by inviting follow-up. If the issue should remain
   open for discussion, say so. If the response effectively
   closes it (e.g. clarification was all that was needed),
   suggest the author may close.

### Flow C — Meta about a generated artefact

Goal: orient the author toward the right doc and clarify the
specific discrepancy / question, without modifying anything.

Structure:

1. **Acknowledge** the question.
2. **Point to the doc that answers it** — use the repo path. If
   the question is about a discrepancy between a spec version
   and a sidecar (e.g. spec says X, validation says Y), explain
   which one is canonical and why. The spec (`output/v<N>-…`) is
   the artefact; the sidecars (`output-analysis/v<N>-…`) are
   analyses *of* the artefact and may surface issues that the
   spec has not yet absorbed.
3. **Opt-out** if the issue is completely off-scope ("this is a
   project-level question; please open a discussion at … or close
   this issue"). Use sparingly — only when there's no way to
   answer constructively.

## Machine-readable meta header

Every response MUST open with a machine-readable HTML comment
block carrying the structured verdict, so `post-response.prompt`
does not have to re-parse the body to decide labels. The block
appears **before** any visible content (before the disclaimer,
before the prose) and has the exact shape:

```html
<!-- sgai-issues-meta:
flow: <A | B | C>
severity: <cosmetic | spec-detail | requirements | architectural>
lang: <en | es | pt | fr | it | de>
cycle: <C>
trusted: <true | false>
conclusion: <resolved | needs-next-step>
conclusion_reason: <short token — see vocabulary below>
-->
```

`conclusion` is the binary token from the "Issue conclusion"
section above, normalised to lowercase-kebab.

`conclusion_reason` is a short text token (one line, no embedded
newlines, no quotes) describing **why** the conclusion went the
way it did. Use a controlled vocabulary so `post-response.prompt`
can log it consistently:

- When `conclusion: resolved`:
  - `resolved-by-pointer` — the response points the raiser at an
    existing file (`context/`, `README.md`, ADR) that answers the
    question.
  - `resolved-by-clarification` — the response clarifies an
    existing decision already on record (`.project/decisions/`).
  - `duplicate` — the issue duplicates a prior issue, ADR, or
    requirement; the response cites it.
  - `out-of-scope` — the issue is out-of-scope for the project;
    the response redirects to the right venue.

- When `conclusion: needs-next-step`:
  - `requires-pr` — the issue requires a future PR against
    `context/` (new requirement, modified UC, new construct,
    wording fix beyond a typo).
  - `requires-adr` — the issue requires a new architectural
    decision; the response sketches the trade-off but the ADR
    must be authored.
  - `requires-wg` — the issue requires working-group input or an
    external standards-body resolution.
  - `requires-clarification` — the AI cannot answer on the merits
    until the raiser clarifies the question; the response asks
    for what's missing.
  - `partial-incorporate` — Flow B with `partial-incorporate`
    recommendation; some parts will land via PR, others are
    deferred / declined.
  - `defer` — Flow B with `defer` recommendation; the response
    explains what would unblock the decision.

The marker is invisible in GitHub's rendered view but readable
when the body is fetched via the API — `post-response.prompt`
parses it (regex on the seven keys) before applying labels.

## Output format

Write `output-github-issues/issue-<N>/cycle-<C>/response.md`
exactly as it should appear when posted. The orchestrator will
pass this file to `gh issue comment --body-file` verbatim in
`--live` mode.

Concretely:

```markdown
<!-- sgai-issues-meta:
flow: B
severity: requirements
lang: en
cycle: 1
trusted: true
conclusion: needs-next-step
conclusion_reason: requires-pr
-->

> <disclaimer line if severity ∈ {requirements, architectural}>

<flow-appropriate body — see structures above>

## Issue conclusion

**NEEDS-NEXT-STEP** — <one-line reason>

<closing rationale paragraph if RESOLVED-BY-RESPONSE, OR
`### Next steps` block if NEEDS-NEXT-STEP — see "Issue
conclusion" section above>

<!-- anti-contradiction: ok -->   (Flow A only; other flows may
                                   omit this line)
<!-- sgai-issues: ai-cycle -->
```

Aim for **concise, decision-friendly drafts**: 200–400 words for
most replies. Longer is fine for `requirements`/`architectural`
issues that warrant more careful framing, but resist padding —
the response is the start of a conversation, not a position
paper. Match the style guidance in `../CLAUDE.md` ("Tone for the
spec and generated artefacts": technical, direct, no fluff).

## Critical do-NOTs

- Do NOT claim that a change has been merged / accepted / shipped.
  The pipeline only drafts; Nicolas is the only one who can
  commit a decision.
- Do NOT promise a timeline beyond what the impact analysis
  supports.
- Do NOT invent ADRs, requirement IDs, or use case IDs. If you
  reference one, verify it exists in `.project/decisions/` or
  `context/`.
- Do NOT translate proper nouns of the spec.
- Do NOT @-mention anyone. The draft addresses the issue
  publicly; pings are for human follow-ups, not auto-drafts.
